### Configure Web Server Launch in Playwright Config

Source: https://github.com/microsoft/playwright/blob/main/docs/src/release-notes-js.md

Configures webServer option in playwright.config.ts to automatically launch a development server before running tests. The server waits for the specified URL to be available before starting tests, and passes the URL as baseURL to Playwright contexts.

```typescript
import { defineConfig } from '@playwright/test';
export default defineConfig({
  webServer: {
    command: 'npm run start',
    url: 'http://127.0.0.1:3000',
    timeout: 120 * 1000,
    reuseExistingServer: !process.env.CI,
  },
});
```

--------------------------------

### Configure a single web server in Playwright Test

Source: https://github.com/microsoft/playwright/blob/main/docs/src/test-api/class-testconfig.md

This example demonstrates how to set up a single web server in `playwright.config.ts`. It specifies the shell command to start the server, the URL Playwright should wait for, a timeout duration, and a condition to reuse an existing server based on the `CI` environment variable. It also configures a `baseURL` for tests to use relative paths.

```js
import { defineConfig } from '@playwright/test';
export default defineConfig({
  webServer: {
    command: 'npm run start',
    url: 'http://localhost:3000',
    timeout: 120 * 1000,
    reuseExistingServer: !process.env.CI,
  },
  use: {
    baseURL: 'http://localhost:3000/',
  },
});
```

--------------------------------

### Configure Playwright test projects in TypeScript

Source: https://github.com/microsoft/playwright/blob/main/docs/src/test-api/class-testconfig.md

This snippet shows how to define multiple test projects using the `projects` property in `playwright.config.ts`. It allows running tests across different configurations, such as various browsers or device types, like 'chromium' with 'Desktop Chrome' settings.

```typescript
import { defineConfig, devices } from '@playwright/test';

export default defineConfig({
  projects: [
    { name: 'chromium', use: devices['Desktop Chrome'] }
  ]
});
```

--------------------------------

### Define Playwright Project Dependencies for Browser Tests (TypeScript)

Source: https://github.com/microsoft/playwright/blob/main/docs/src/test-projects-js.md

This Playwright configuration demonstrates how to define project dependencies. A 'setup' project is configured to run first, matching all `.setup.ts` files. Subsequently, 'chromium', 'firefox', and 'webkit' browser projects are defined, each explicitly depending on the 'setup' project to ensure setup actions complete before browser tests begin.

```typescript
import { defineConfig, devices } from '@playwright/test';

export default defineConfig({
  projects: [
    {
      name: 'setup',
      testMatch: '**/*.setup.ts',
    },
    {
      name: 'chromium',
      use: { ...devices['Desktop Chrome'] },
      dependencies: ['setup'],
    },
    {
      name: 'firefox',
      use: { ...devices['Desktop Firefox'] },
      dependencies: ['setup'],
    },
    {
      name: 'webkit',
      use: { ...devices['Desktop Safari'] },
      dependencies: ['setup'],
    },
  ],
});
```

--------------------------------

### Define Playwright Configuration with Global Setup and Base URL

Source: https://github.com/microsoft/playwright/blob/main/docs/src/test-global-setup-teardown-js.md

This `playwright.config.ts` snippet illustrates how to integrate the global setup function into your Playwright test configuration. It specifies the path to the `globalSetup` file, defines a `baseURL` for tests, and sets the `storageState` file path where authentication state will be stored and retrieved.

```js
import { defineConfig } from '@playwright/test';
export default defineConfig({
  globalSetup: require.resolve('./global-setup'),
  use: {
    baseURL: 'http://localhost:3000/',
    storageState: 'state.json',
  },
});
```

