### Fill form and verify with Playwright locators

Source: https://github.com/microsoft/playwright/blob/main/docs/src/release-notes-js.md

Demonstrates using Playwright's new locator APIs to interact with form elements and verify page content. Uses getByLabel to fill input fields, getByRole to click buttons, and getByText with assertions to verify successful form submission. Requires Playwright test environment setup.

```javascript
await page.getByLabel('User Name').fill('John');

await page.getByLabel('Password').fill('secret-password');

await page.getByRole('button', { name: 'Sign in' }).click();

await expect(page.getByText('Welcome, John!')).toBeVisible();
```

--------------------------------

### Write First Playwright Test - JavaScript

Source: https://github.com/microsoft/playwright/blob/main/docs/src/writing-tests-js.md

Basic Playwright test demonstrating page navigation and assertions. Tests verify page title contains 'Playwright' and check for visible elements using role-based locators. Requires @playwright/test package.

```javascript
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('has title', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('https://playwright.dev/');

  // Expect a title "to contain" a substring.
  await expect(page).toHaveTitle(/Playwright/);
});

test('get started link', async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto('https://playwright.dev/');

  // Click the get started link.
  await page.getByRole('link', { name: 'Get started' }).click();

  // Expects page to have a heading with the name of Installation.
  await expect(page.getByRole('heading', { name: 'Installation' })).toBeVisible();
});
```

--------------------------------

### Basic Playwright Test with Assertions and Locators - Java

Source: https://github.com/microsoft/playwright/blob/main/docs/src/writing-tests-java.md

Complete example test demonstrating Playwright setup, navigation, assertions, and element interaction. Creates a browser instance, navigates to a page, validates title and attributes, and performs click actions using locators with auto-wait functionality.

```java
package org.example;

import java.util.regex.Pattern;
import com.microsoft.playwright.*;
import com.microsoft.playwright.options.AriaRole;

import static com.microsoft.playwright.assertions.PlaywrightAssertions.assertThat;

public class App {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try (Playwright playwright = Playwright.create()) {
            Browser browser = playwright.chromium().launch();
            Page page = browser.newPage();
            page.navigate("https://playwright.dev");

            // Expect a title "to contain" a substring.
            assertThat(page).hasTitle(Pattern.compile("Playwright"));

            // create a locator
            Locator getStarted = page.getByRole(AriaRole.LINK, new Page.GetByRoleOptions().setName("Get Started"));

            // Expect an attribute "to be strictly equal" to the value.
            assertThat(getStarted).hasAttribute("href", "/docs/intro");

            // Click the get started link.
            getStarted.click();

            // Expects page to have a heading with the name of Installation.
            assertThat(page.getByRole(AriaRole.HEADING,
               new Page.GetByRoleOptions().setName("Installation"))).isVisible();
        }
    }
}
```

--------------------------------

### Create Locator and Click Element - JavaScript

Source: https://github.com/microsoft/playwright/blob/main/docs/src/writing-tests-js.md

Locate elements using Playwright's Locators API with role-based selectors and perform click actions. Playwright automatically waits for actionability before executing the action. Can be written as single-line or multi-line statements.

```javascript
// Create a locator.
const getStarted = page.getByRole('link', { name: 'Get started' });

// Click it.
await getStarted.click();
```

```javascript
await page.getByRole('link', { name: 'Get started' }).click();
```

--------------------------------

### Assert Locator Text Content in Playwright

Source: https://github.com/microsoft/playwright/blob/main/docs/src/api/class-locatorassertions.md

This example demonstrates how to assert that a Playwright `Locator`'s text content matches a specific string. It typically involves performing an action, such as clicking a button, and then using `expect(locator).toHaveText()` to verify the resulting text of an element. This assertion automatically waits for the condition to be met.

```js
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('status becomes submitted', async ({ page }) => {
  // ...
  await page.getByRole('button').click();
  await expect(page.locator('.status')).toHaveText('Submitted');
});
```

```java
import static com.microsoft.playwright.assertions.PlaywrightAssertions.assertThat;

public class TestLocator {
  // ...
  @Test
  void statusBecomesSubmitted() {
    // ...
    page.getByRole(AriaRole.BUTTON).click();
    assertThat(page.locator(".status")).hasText("Submitted");
  }
}
```

```python
from playwright.async_api import Page, expect

async def test_status_becomes_submitted(page: Page) -> None:
    # ..
    await page.get_by_role("button").click()
    await expect(page.locator(".status")).to_have_text("Submitted")
```

```python
from playwright.sync_api import Page, expect

def test_status_becomes_submitted(page: Page) -> None:
    # ..
    page.get_by_role("button").click()
    expect(page.locator(".status")).to_have_text("Submitted")
```

```csharp
using Microsoft.Playwright;
using Microsoft.Playwright.MSTest;

namespace PlaywrightTests;

[TestClass]
public class ExampleTests : PageTest
{
    [TestMethod]
    public async Task StatusBecomesSubmitted()
    {
        // ...
        await Page.GetByRole(AriaRole.Button, new() { Name = "Sign In" }).ClickAsync();
        await Expect(Page.Locator(".status")).ToHaveTextAsync("Submitted");
    }
}
```

